docs.lead_paragraph: SHEPHERD, Texas — When Jamie Williams decided to reopen her East Texas tattoo studio last week in defiance of the state’s coronavirus restrictions, she asked Philip Archibald for help. He showed up with his dog Zeus, his friends and his AR-15 semiautomatic rifle.

headline.main: Businesses Chafing Under Covid-19 Lockdowns Turn to Armed Defiance

byline.original: By Manny Fernandez and David Montgomery

docs.lead_paragraph: In his first Inaugural Address, and hopefully his last, Donald Trump talked about American carnage. He got it this week. What we couldn’t have known in January 2017 is that he wasn’t here to save us from this carnage, but to perpetuate it; that incitement wasn’t just a feature of his campaign, but of his governance. When historians look back at the Trump era, they may very well say his presidency was encapsulated by this moment, when a sadistic cop knelt on the neck of an African-American man for almost nine minutes in plain view and the streets exploded in rage.

headline.main: What Trump and Toxic Cops Have in Common
headline.print_headline: What Trump and Toxic Cops Have in Common

docs.abstract: We grew up in a family of activists. I wanted everyone to see his calm bravery.
docs.snippet: We grew up in a family of activists. I wanted everyone to see his calm bravery.
docs.lead_paragraph: I grew up in a family of activists and my parents were teachers. They raised me and my brother, Chris, to never shy from fighting injustice. From police brutality, to the war in Iraq, to climate change, we’ve lifted our voices in protest. So when I saw Chris’s video of his recent encounter with a white woman named Amy Cooper (no relation) in New York’s Central Park, it was surreal that he had captured on his cellphone the kind of racism we had always railed against. All of a sudden, I became one of the hundreds of black women who have watched a video of a loved one being accosted.

headline.main: Chris Cooper Is My Brother. Here’s Why I Posted His Video.

docs.abstract: Racial strife, consent, wealth inequality: The issues swirling in these fantastical settings may seem familiar.
docs.snippet: Racial strife, consent, wealth inequality: The issues swirling in these fantastical settings may seem familiar.
docs.lead_paragraph: Plans, like time, have proved remarkably elastic during this pandemic, and books I’d intended to discuss here have been delayed half a season or more, while books I didn’t cover upon their release have taken on new significance. So consider this column a chaotic pantry from which to prepare a week’s worth of meals: Here are six very different books, remarkable enough in their difference, I hope, to feed at least that many different hungers.

headline.main: Visit These Science-Fiction Worlds to Make Sense of Our Own

docs.lead_paragraph: Minnesota’s top officials acknowledged early Saturday morning that they had underestimated the destruction that protesters in Minneapolis were capable of inflicting as a newly issued curfew did little to stop people from burning buildings and turning the city’s streets into a smoky battleground.

headline.main: ‘Absolute Chaos’ in Minneapolis as Protests Grow Across U.S.
